Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

### 1. Create a custom `Window` subclass

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
        {
            vm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}
```

### Key points

- **`OnStopped`** — fires when the app is fully backgrounded; save the draft here.
- **`OnResumed`** — fires when returning from background; restore the draft.
- **`OnDestroying`** — also save here because Android's back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small strings — it's fast and synchronous, which matters because lifecycle handlers must complete quickly (~1–2 seconds) to avoid ANR on Android or watchdog kills on iOS.
- **`Resumed` does not fire on first launch** (the sequence is `Created` → `Activated`), so load any persisted draft in your page's `OnAppearing` or viewmodel constructor for the cold-start case.
